One week ago today, two terrorists killed 14 people in my city...21 others were wounded. I'm a photographer for the newspaper here and ever since that morning, I've been working long days that have been mentally, physically and emotionally exhausting. Today is my first day back at the gym since before the attack and it feels great to push my body and clear my mind. 
If you're the praying type, please lift up the city of San Bernardino...the families who lost loved ones...and pray for the hearts of terrorists...that they be changed and used for good.

The events of last Wednesday haven't hit me yet. Two people did the unthinkable in the place I call "home"... And when I was told what happened, I didn't think much about it at first. Maybe I've become numb to violence - who knows - but as I witnessed the outpouring of love and support for the 14 died and 21 wounded from the terrorist attack on Dec. 2, it made me want to believe in people again. There was this kindness after tragedy. Love. Hugs. Humanity. I'm so proud to call myself a San Bernardino resident, proud to have graduated from San Bernardino High School, and proud to know many local heroes. (Jack Brown! Margaret Hill!) This Cardinal believes San Bernardino will rise from the ashes, as do the Cowboys, Knights, Spartans, etc. of this community. I, like this city, is #SBStrong. ‚ù§Ô∏è

DEC. 9 - MOMENT OF SILENCE & VIGIL

On Dec. 9, San Bernardino Valley College will hold a campus-wide moment of silence at 11:00am. Please stop whatever you are doing at that time to honor the victims of the tragedy at the Inland Regional Center on December 2.

At 11:30, a campus-wide Vigil will be held in the Greek Theater  to remember the victims, their families and loved ones.

All campus offices will be closed at 11:15-12:30. Faculty are encouraged to bring their classes to participate. This event is open to the public.

üò™üíî It's been a very sad and scary week here in Southern California. I wish it was all just a bad dream but sadly it's not. My thoughts and prayers are with those in San Bernardino that lost their lives, the families and friends that lost loved ones and those that were injured and effected by this senseless tragedy. caption.text:
It has been hard to figure out how to deal with the recent #violence, especially when it hits so close to home, in #SanBernardino. But I know people have a strong need for #community, and a need to be heard. There is also a need to reach out and engage in some cross-cultural dialogue, so when my friend Eli, who I know from the #policeaccountability movement up in the #HighDesert, told me some of the #blackpastors reached out to him wanting to do a #vigil, I was down to help get people together. It was a little bit of a strange mix, tbh, cause it's not every day that members of the #AfricanAmerican community gather with #immigrantrights #organizers to mourn and pray--add to that the unexpected participation of some #electedofficials (I think you can see #NormaTorres and #CherylBrown in one of the pictures) and members of the #RCP and you get an even stranger mix--but despite all that I think it went really well!
I mean what else can you really do? Times like this call for #prayer, as long as we can respect each others' different ways of #praying. There was also talk of the need to take #action--everything from being wary of #xenophobia in the streets and in the statehouse, to needing to do something about the day-to-day violence that plagues our community, especially in places like San Bernardino. #SanBernardinoshooting #SBstrong #inlandempire

We remember tonight that even in the midst of adversity, we fight on. We remember that fear will not stop us from living our lives. An incredible moment of silence before the game tonight as we remembered the lives lost in this terrible tragedy. The beauty of this game is that for 60 minutes the world stops. Even if only for a moment, the game transcended all of the insanity, and for four quarters our only adversary was the Las Vegas Legends. The Fury battled tonight and made their fans and their city proud. #SBStrong #FuryStrong

Although the San Bernardino area has a large populace, everyone I know seems to have a personal  connection to this tragedy.  Bike riding friends, student's parents at my school, one of the deceased from our own neighboring city of Highland, another connection discovered almost every new conversation.  Six fellow teachers and our principal had the privilege of taking time during lunch today to go place flowers at one of the memorial sites down the street from the IRC. Although small, I'm sure this memorial will grow once Waterman Avenue in front of the IRC opens.  It felt good to go do this, to talk and pray with the Billy Graham sponsored Chaplains that were present and talking with folks that milled around.  It felt good to drive down San Bernardino Avenue right where the final shoot out occurred to mentally reclaim our streets that we frequent in both car and on bike. #sbstrong

last night at the candle light vigil for the victims of the mass shooting that took place Wednesday morning. üïØ

The two victims names that were read out that stuck out with me the most were Damian Meins & Nicolas Thalasinos.  I was at the community center where the victims were being transported to be reunited with their families.  There were these 3 women, appearing to be a wife & 2 daughters with looks of concern & sadness after the last bus of victims were dropped off at the community center in which their loved one they were looking for wasn't on that bus. 
They walked up to a sheriff chaplain voicing their concern, saying how they called every hospital and they had no record of the loved one they were looking for and asking what to do next. They then were asked if they would like to receive prayer in which they accepted with no hesitation. I, as well as my mother & a member from our church got up & joined hands with the women as they prayed for their missing loved one, Damian Meins. After prayer was over, hugs were exchanged then they were lead back into the community centers gym where the news was broken that he had no made it.. earlier before that I heard a woman on the phone, spelling out the name "Nicolas Thalasinos" appearing to be calling a hospital to see if he was at any of them. It stuck out to me because she also said his birthday out loud. It really caught my attention due to the fact we shared the same birth day & month. "10/14" I'll never forget that day... Later when the victims names were released, I got the chills reading those two names... prayers are with the families affected as well as this city which is my home... may all the victims rest in peace, & their families find comfort in this dark time.
#PrayForTheDino #SBStrong #12215

caption.text: #prayforsanbernardino #SBStrong

After the horrible shooting in San Bernardino yesterday (December 2, 2015), I wanted to remember what that city was like in happier times. Like when my husband and I lived there in the 1980s. So I chose this picture for Throwback Thursday this week. My Father took this when he came out to visit me for Christmas in 1987. Hershel's Deli was one of our favorite restaurants. We always ate breakfast there and loved it. Unfortunately, Hershel's Deli closed in 1989, at about the time I left San Bernardino. #sanbernardino #throwbackthursday #prayforsanbernardino #prayforsb #tbt #inlandempire #1987 #1980s #restaurant #picoftheday #sbstrong

#prayforsanbernardino Crazy how we were just there a couple days ago rembering when we use to live there, jump on the 15 to go to school, and his job right off waterman :( I almost got a job through school to work for SB county but with budget cuts it didn't last. Can't believe something so tragic happened to a place that holds a special spot in my heart. San Bernardino is a working class city that like any other city has its good and bad. From its beautiful mountain terrain to the hustle and bustle of downtown. #sanberdoo #csusb #mtvernonswapmeet #sb #sbstrong #workingclass #humanity #inlandempire #ie

It hurts to always see my hometown in negative headlines. I took this picture just after San Bernardino declared bankruptcy and shortly before i left to college. But San Bernardino was a perfect place for me to grow up filled with amazing opportunity and great people. I send positive thoughts to all of those affected by this tragedy and I know that this will only make San Bernardino stronger and more unified. #sanbernardino #sanbernardinostrong #sbstrong #prayforsanbernardino
